# Smooth Canvas Dragging Implementation Plan

This plan outlines the approach to eliminate React's `setState` bottleneck during layer dragging (translating) and resizing, addressing the "super duper smooth" requirement.

## User Review Required
> [!IMPORTANT]
> The current system re-renders the entire canvas on every mouse move when dragging. This plan moves to a direct-DOM-mutation approach using `requestAnimationFrame` and GSAP/DOM APIs during the drag, and only syncs back to React (`setRectangleLayers`) when the pointer is released (`onPointerUp`). I need your approval to modify `Canvas.tsx` to handle this.

## Proposed Changes

### `Canvas.tsx`

#### [MODIFY] [canvas.tsx](file:///c:/Users/HP/Downloads/lair/lair/client/src/components/board/canvas/canvas.tsx)
- **Ref-Based Mutability:** 
  - Stop calling `setRectangleLayers` inside `onPointerMove` when `canvasState.mode === CanvasMode.Translating`.
  - Instead, retrieve the dragged DOM elements using `layerRefs.current.get(item.id)`.
- **`requestAnimationFrame` loop:**
  - Wrap the `onPointerMove` DOM updates inside `requestAnimationFrame` to ensure updates are synchronized with the display refresh rate.
  - Apply `x` and `y` properties to the elements (using `gsap.set` or direct `setAttribute` for SVGs).
- **Selection Box Handling:**
  - Since the `SelectionBox` won't re-render via state, we will assign it a ref (`selectionBoxRef`) and update its `transform` or coordinates synchronously with the dragged items.
- **WebSocket Throttling:**
  - Maintain the existing throttled cursor/layer broadcast so remote cursors are still accurately informed of the partial movement.
- **Finalizing State (onPointerUp):**
  - In `onPointerUp`, calculate the final resting positions of the layers and perform a single `setRectangleLayers` to synchronize the React state with the visual result.

### `SelectionBox.tsx`

#### [MODIFY] [selection-box.tsx](file:///c:/Users/HP/Downloads/lair/lair/client/src/components/board/selection-box.tsx)
- Update it to forward a ref to its DOM container `<g>` element, allowing `canvas.tsx` to directly mutate its transform during a drag without causing a re-render.

## Open Questions
- Do you want to apply this same `refs instead of state` logic immediately to the **resizing** function as well, or just **translating** (dragging) for now? (Resizing is slightly more complex conceptually but uses the same ref-mutation pattern).

## Verification Plan
1. Start dragging a complex set of layers (e.g. 5+ rectangles).
2. Measure FPS or visually confirm that React dev tools do not highlight a full canvas re-render on every pixel moved.
3. Validate that releasing the mouse click correctly plots the final position into history and the real state.
